<h2><a href="http://thinkvitamin.com/web-apps/building-in-a-burning-house-tools-for-damn%e2%80%99-downtime/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to Building in a Burning House: Tools for Damnâ€™ Downtime">Building in a Burning House: Tools for Damnâ€™ Downtime</a></h2>
<p class="postDetails">By <a href="http://thinkvitamin.com/author/chrissiebrodigan/" title="Posts by Chrissie Brodigan">Chrissie Brodigan</a> | 16 December 2010 | Category: <a href="http://thinkvitamin.com/category/web-apps/" title="View all posts in Web Apps" rel="category tag">Web Apps</a></p>
<p>When you provide a web service, uptime is a big <em>f&amp;$king</em> deal.</p>
<p>If you build a web app and grow a core and vibrant user base, at some  point you might find yourself building inside a burning  house.*</p>
<p>$hi% happens, and it can happen during the most innocuous upgrades  and maintenance, and working with your designers to design for downtime  (ahead of time) can be tremendously helpful and set you apart from your  competitors. You can have uptime somewhere on the web, you just need to design for its delivery.</p>
 
